Mental Health and Food Access

Raveena, Alanna, Jack

12/8/2021

Introduction

The question we seek to answer is how does food access impact adult mental health across the United States? Many factors affect mental health, food access has many effects, and they are likely related. We hypothesize that reduced access to food increases poor mental health.

Prior Research

Seligman and Schillinger (2010) posit that food insecurity and chronic disease follows a cyclical pattern where food insecurity leads to chronic disease, thereby increasing medical costs and causing low income households to make trade-offs in spending, often leading to less money available to address food insecurity. Additionally, the results of Jones (2017) suggests that individual food insecurity is associated with poorer mental health and specific psychosocial stressors across global regions independent of socio-ecoomic status.

Data

Categorical

  • Access to food options within 1 mile urban or 10 miles rural (USDA)
  • Education, most common attainment per census tract (US census)

Continuous

  • Percent of adults experiencing poor mental health for 14 days or more (CDC)
  • Percent of households using SNAP (USDA)
  • Poverty rate (USDA)
  • Median income (US census)
  • Percent of households with children (US census)
  • Median Age (US census)
  • Race (US census)

This dataset includes 72,351 census tracts across the United States.

Methods

We ran a multivariate linear regression of the independent variables in this analysis to examine their effects on the percent of people experiencing fourteen or more poor mental health days per year, across the United States at the scale of the census tract. If the model has significant and negative coefficients for the SNAP usage variable, this indicates that increased usage of SNAP benefits is associated with less poor mental health outcomes. Similarly, if the coefficient for food access based on USDA definitions is significant and negative, this means an area of food access is correlated with less poor mental health.

Our dependent variable is the percent of adults in a census tract experiencing poor mental health for 14 days or more. The independent variables included are percent of population utilizing SNAP benefits, poverty rate, median income, median age, percent of households with children, if the census tract has high access to food (based on 1 mile for urban areas and 10 miles for rural areas), the most common highest educational attainment within the census tract, and the percent of population that identify as one of the following racial categories: white, Black, American Indian/Alaska Native, Asian, Native Hawiian, or two or more. The racial category of other was excluded from the regression to avoid a singularity, since all of the racial categories would add up to 100%. This would yield multicollinearity such that the regression would not be completed for all racial demographic variables. We chose to exclude other since it revealed the least information, as it is the broadest grouping within this part of the census.

We first scaled the continuous variables to represent whole numbers rather than percentages and to represent age by decades and median income by units of one million. This transformed the coefficient to be more legible in the context of the tables.

In an alternate model we transformed the data by taking the base 2 log of median income. Income could be better described using a logarithmic model to show how a doubling of income affects poor mental health. In a third option for a model, we included an interaction between percent SNAP utilization and food access by distance. This interaction could be important because SNAP utilization might change depending on if someone has access to food nearby; if someone doesnt live near a grocery store, they wouldnt have an opportunity to use their SNAP benefits.

The Initial, Median Income Logged, and Median Income Logged and SNAP: Food Access Interaction models all have high R squared values of 0.84, 0.85, and 0.85 respectively. The Interaction Model is our preferred model, even though it didnt improve the fit compared to the Median Income Logged Model. Adding in the interaction variable provides another level of detail that can stimulate further research questions.

All of the independent variables have p-values as close to 0 that R will compute, except for the Professional Degree education category and % Race Two or More. The Professional Degree education category has a p-value below 0.05 and % Race Two or More has a p-value below 0.01, so these are still somewhat significant.

The R-squared values are 0.84 and 0.85, so this combination of independent variables explains 84 to 85% of the variation in percent of the population experiencing poor mental health for more than 14 days. These are high R squared values, which could suggest that poor mental health is well predicted by the independent variables we included in this regression. Based on our research question, we now look at the Food Access variable. With respect to a census tract without food access (as defined by the USDA), the coefficient is -0.00, indicating a very small decrease in adults reporting poor mental health for more than 14 days.

Discussion

The results of this analysis support our hypothesis regarding food access as the USDA food access variable is negatively correlated with increased poor mental health days. Being in close proximity to reliable food sources reduces the stress and challenges associated with procuring food which can contribute to better nutrition to support both physical and mental health. However in the context of this study, the estimate is the second smallest suggesting that the distance aspect of food access does not have a strong influence on mental health outcomes in adults. This does not mean other components of food access do not influence mental health outcomes, such as quality, transportation, and affordability.

The results do not support our hypothesis regarding SNAP usage, which is positively correlated with increased poor mental health days. SNAP is a food stamp program that assists low-income individuals, so higher SNAP utilization may indicate lower financial security resulting in poor mental health. Any improvement in mental health from the ability to access food via SNAP benefits is not revealed in this analysis, and is likely negated by other effects of low financial security.

The interaction between SNAP utilization and food access and the effects on mental health is a surprising result, as we had expected to see increased food access by distance lessen the percentage of the population affected by poor mental health days. Understanding the cause of this correlation would likely require more information about the areas of food access, potentially narrowing the geographic scope of the analysis, and using qualitative methods to better understand the implications of geographic food access and financial food access in peoples daily lives.

Other correlations revealed in this analysis can be understood when considering how financial security affects mental health. The positive correlation with increased Poverty Rate indicates lower financial security and units with children may present lower financial security given the additional mouths to feed and children to care for, both of which result in poor mental health. Regarding education, GED and High School are the lowest attainable levels of education in the census and could result in lower income overall, meaning that financial security is lower and negatively impacts mental health. Bachelors, masters, and doctorate degrees are the highest levels of educational attainment which suggests these census tracts likely also have higher incomes and greater financial security, both factors that could reduce the likelihood of persisting poor mental health in adults. If there are other factors in these correlations other than financial security, further analysis would be needed to identify those variables that lead to the outcomes shown in this analysis. For example, the correlations between race and mental health reflect our understanding of how racial discrimination and systemic racism towards non-white individuals can contribute to higher levels of hypertension and stress.

A weakness of this analysis is the reliance on proxy variables to represent income, wealth, and financial security, all of which have complex interactions on both food access and mental health. More precision and less overlap in the variables to hold constant should improve this regression analysis, potentially by picking just one variable to describe financial security. However, the complexity of these interactions does not suggest one clear choice, so multiple analyses are likely necessary to identify which variable best represents the financial component of mental health.

With the data available, further analysis should separate SNAP usage and USDA food access to look at the effects of each independently on mental health. A more robust and precise analysis would look at a more narrow segment of the population. For example, the effects of SNAP usage on mental health could analyze people who are close to the eligibility threshold so the populations are likely similar and SNAP usage can be a single independent variable. Similarly, looking at the geographic fringes of food access and identifying people who are close to the radius of 1 mile in urban areas and 10 miles in rural areas could reveal the effects of geographic food access on mental health.

Conclusion

The results of our study support the findings of Jones (2017) and further demonstrate that factors that contribute to individual food security are also associated with poor mental health outcomes. They also demonstrate that demographic factors that contribute to financial insecurity such as median income, SNAP utilization, number of children, lower educational attainment levels, and race influence mental health in adults. Our study also revealed that factors directly related to food access, such as physical proximity to food and financial assistance through SNAP, do not necessarily lead to fewer poor mental health days. This leads to more questions for further research: what other factors cause the difference in mental health as correlated with SNAP usage when comparing areas of high food access to areas of low food access?

In context to planning practice, our study highlights the need to analyze multiple socio-economic factors and their possible interactions when assessing food access and health outcomes in a population. Simply increasing the number of food options or an individuals ability to access them through a subsidy or voucher is not enough and needs to work in tandem with other people-based and place-based interventions that reduce barriers to an individual achieving financial security. Additionally, food access and mental health outcomes should be independently studied at the local level to fully understand existing dynamics and the unique circumstances a population might face in a particular location.
